      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "This is a very common and understandable concern, as schools do have the authority to set curricular standards based on educational goals and community consensus. While many families may view gender identity education as personal, schools often frame it as essential for fostering inclusivity, bullying prevention, and social-emotional learning for *all* students. Because opinions vary so widely, schools frequently involve parents in decision-making processes to ensure the content is approved before implementation, though disagreements can still arise.",
